me from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Percy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":11,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A fa